00:01:57.720 --> 00:02:05.480
Like a very quick introduction, the crash course to CSS, what is it? CSS is basically how the

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:13.240
internet describes the way that elements are displayed on a page. Basically, it lets you

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:21.240
control multiple elements by the usage of classes and selectors. And basically, it's made of very

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:28.839
small instructions, which are called statements. Statements do simply two things. They identify

00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:34.919
an object in the page, and they declare a value for a specific property of that element.

00:02:35.639 --> 00:02:40.759
This is a very simple example of what a CSS statement would look like. You can see we're

00:02:40.759 --> 00:02:46.600
styling something that has a class of search box, and we're styling the border in the background of

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:51.639
that specific element. The cool thing with CSS is if you have two elements, or ten elements,

00:02:51.639 --> 00:02:56.919
or 50 elements with this specific class, they will all be affected by this specific group.

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:04.759
So, why is this really important for Shiny? The thing is, every web page right now,

00:03:04.759 --> 00:03:11.399
in some way or another, uses CSS, and Shiny is no exception. So, even though you're programming

00:03:11.399 --> 00:03:16.759
in ARIA, and you're building this Shiny application, behind the scenes, what's actually

00:03:16.759 --> 00:03:22.520
happening is that Shiny is generating some JavaScript, some HTML, some CSS, and the key

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:29.639
part here is the CSS. So, because some CSS is being generated, we can also add our own on top

00:03:29.639 --> 00:03:39.000
of it. So, how would we actually go about doing this? So, with Shiny itself, there's three very

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:45.080
specific ways that you can do it. So, you can add the style directly to your tags when you're

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:52.520
building your UI. You can add it as, let's say, a separate tag in the header of your page, or

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:58.440
your application, but you can also store it in files and link those files directly to the Shiny

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:07.240
application. So, for the first one, whatever you create in your UI, as long as it's an HTML tag,

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:14.839
you can always pass a special style attribute, which lets you basically pass any kind of

00:04:15.639 --> 00:04:22.600
CSS statement that will affect that specific element. So, here, there's no statements,

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:26.519
there's no classes, there's nothing. This is style that you want to apply to that specific

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:37.880
element. And, this is fine. This is okay. But, to be honest, this is probably, this should be your

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:45.079
last resort when it comes to adding CSS to Shiny. The truth is that, by adding, it's fine if you

00:04:45.079 --> 00:04:49.559
have one or two elements, but when you get to 10, 20, 50 elements, when you start having very

00:04:49.559 --> 00:04:59.160
complex UIs, you lose track of where you style the specific thing. You cannot reuse any rules.

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:04.440
So, if you have three titles, you need to style the three titles. It's very hard to keep consistency

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:11.640
between all the elements. This is something that, if you use BSLib, for example, it's all for you,

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:16.920
because there's general rules that affect every element, but if you're doing these individual

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:21.640
changes, you won't be able to actually keep track of them as your project grows.

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:28.839
The second way would be to add CSS to your header. So, this is slightly better. This is,

00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:37.720
you can add a style tag with some text inside, and that text can be CSS text. This is slightly

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:45.480
better. This does mean that you can use those selectors. You can apply the same styling to a

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:53.320
lot of elements at the same time, but at the same time, you won't really be able to leverage the

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:59.559
browser here, because you're generating the CSS whenever the page is created. This actually means

00:05:59.559 --> 00:06:07.480
that your browser won't be able to cache these. By caching, I mean saving them for future usage

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:14.679
when you reopen the application later. So, you end up having a slightly better approach,

00:06:14.679 --> 00:06:21.640
but at the same time, it's still not the ideal approach. So, we can always do the third option.

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:29.480
So, this would be to create a file with all of our CSS on the side, link this file to our Shiny

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:34.600
application, and then the browser actually has something that it can save for the future,

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:40.920
and at the same time, we have a specific place where we have all our styling neatly saved,

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:48.200
packed away from our code, from our logic. This is much better. This is probably the best

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:54.200
approach you can take if you're using just regular CSS. You can reuse the code,

00:06:54.200 --> 00:07:00.600
you can reuse the rules, you can cache these files, your browser can leverage the cache to

00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:07.320
actually save these files for later. It also allows you to kind of separate your styling into multiple

00:07:07.320 --> 00:07:15.720
files and start adding a bit of structure to how you're saving styling for different elements,

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:21.880
for different modules. However, CSS is still something that can get very complex,

00:07:21.880 --> 00:07:27.559
and it's kind of this thing that grows out of control very fast as your project grows.

00:07:27.559 --> 00:07:30.040
So, there's still a bit of room for improvement here.

00:07:30.760 --> 00:07:38.440
So, one way that you can improve this workflow even better is to use SaaS. So, SaaS is,

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:47.079
as Tom mentioned before, this is a language built on top of CSS, and the idea here is that it's

00:07:47.959 --> 00:07:55.959
preprocessor to CSS, so any SaaS that you create always ends up being CSS, but there's this layer

00:07:56.359 --> 00:08:03.239
of obstruction where you have a few different tools, and you don't really need to worry about

00:08:03.239 --> 00:08:09.239
creating very complex or managing very complex CSS, because SaaS gives you a couple of ways of

00:08:09.239 --> 00:08:14.279
managing it a bit better. So, a couple of differences here between SaaS and CSS are

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:21.559
SaaS is object-oriented, so this means that you can have nesting, it's more about the concept of what

00:08:21.559 --> 00:08:25.880
is a specific element that you're trying to target, not the specific element that you're

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:33.400
targeting. It also allows variables. I know that CSS3 is actually pushing forward with variables

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:41.799
in CSS. This is, I think, a very nice bonus, but it's one of the things that SaaS, at least

00:08:41.799 --> 00:08:47.400
my understanding, still does much better than just CSS. And also, you can always use SaaS

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:57.000
to actually generate CSS variables to reuse in the future. So, a couple of really interesting

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:02.760
things that you can do with SaaS. So, we talked about nesting, so what nesting means is that you

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:09.640
can simplify a lot of the rules that you do by nesting them. So, as you can see, CSS doesn't,

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:14.359
CSS on the right side doesn't really allow for this, so if you're targeting two different

00:09:14.359 --> 00:09:19.799
elements, in this case, for example, a UL and an LI element inside of an app bar, you're going to

00:09:19.799 --> 00:09:26.440
need to create the full selector every time you create a rule. SaaS kind of solves this by

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:34.359
allowing nesting, so if you have two elements inside the same elements, you can kind of nest

00:09:34.359 --> 00:09:43.640
them together and simplify your code even a tiny bit more. We also talked about variables, so CSS

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:50.280
does allow variables, but SaaS does it in a way that you can kind of declare them, even in separate

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:55.719
files, completely different. There's no scope required, which is something that CSS variables

00:09:55.719 --> 00:10:04.039
need, and you can simply use them by assigning a name to a property that starts with a dollar sign,

00:10:04.039 --> 00:10:07.880
and then just this becomes a variable that you can use throughout your code.

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:17.960
It also has two very important mechanisms, which are extents and mixins, so extents is kind of,

00:10:18.599 --> 00:10:25.320
and this is something that is very well explained with an example, so it basically

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:31.080
allows you to share styles between selectors, and the way that you would do this normally in

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:36.200
CSS, if you would have two elements that you would like to style, even though they are very similar,

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:42.200
is that you would simply do the styling for both of them. By using extend, you can actually create

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:52.039
a partial part of code by using the percentage as a marker for the name of that block of code,

00:10:52.039 --> 00:11:00.119
and you can then extend for each element, you can simply extend the name, the extent

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:06.919
rule that you created, and the code will actually be copied into that selector, so this means that

00:11:06.919 --> 00:11:16.760
you can reuse parts of styling that you use very often by simply extracting them into a separate

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:24.119
name that you can then reuse. The second one is mixins, so mixins are slightly similar, but

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:31.880
these work more like functions, so the idea here is that instead of simply taking out a piece of

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:37.080
a block of code and saving it with a name, with a mixin, you're actually having a function,

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:43.320
so this means that you can pass specific arguments to those functions that you're creating,

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:48.200
so in this case, for example, we've identified that the only difference between these two

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:54.919
components is actually the border size, so we can create a mixin that has an argument of border

00:11:54.919 --> 00:12:00.440
size and simply call those functions in each of our declarations for each specific element.

00:12:02.599 --> 00:12:09.239
So, a small introduction of Sass, a very big, a very crash course-y kind of thing, but hopefully

00:12:09.239 --> 00:12:16.280
it shows you some of the advantages that you actually have. So, how do you actually use this

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:21.640
with R? So, the best way, of course, is to use a library, and RStudio was kind enough to actually

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:32.280
create a really nice package for us, so you can use RSass to not have to worry about all the

00:12:32.280 --> 00:12:38.599
pre-processing, you just need to write code, this is all you want to do, and in general, the package

00:12:38.599 --> 00:12:45.000
gives you one big function called sass, and this sass function can take either a string or a full

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.479
file and just returns the CSS to you. So, all of these techniques that we've been talking

00:12:51.479 --> 00:13:01.159
about, you know, I've accessed them inside of R directly without actually having to

00:13:01.159 --> 00:13:09.479
work outside of our files. The second way is actually, you can actually pass it a reference

00:13:09.479 --> 00:13:14.760
to a file. So, here, for example, we're simply pointing the sass function to our style's main

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:21.239
file, and this file has a lot of internal stuff for sass, and this way, you can kind of

00:13:22.599 --> 00:13:29.320
tile all of your, you can kind of split all of your styling into something that behaves a bit

00:13:29.320 --> 00:13:36.280
more like code managing, and actually lets you reuse a lot of the styles and kind of keep a grasp

00:13:36.359 --> 00:13:42.119
of styles when it comes to very big projects. A second argument that's very important in this

00:13:42.119 --> 00:13:47.080
function is the output. So, the output will generate that CSS to a specific file, and then

00:13:47.080 --> 00:13:53.320
this is something that you can simply add to your UI, and now you have all of your styles

00:13:53.320 --> 00:14:02.679
saved in a project folder structure that has everything well sorted, and you can kind of

00:14:02.679 --> 00:14:11.799
manage them. If you would like to see an example of sass being used very extensively, I will point

00:14:11.799 --> 00:14:19.880
you to my Shiny contest entry from last year. I've used sass quite a lot, and hopefully it will guide

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:28.760
you in the right way to get started. Yeah, and I think my 15 minutes are up, and I would just

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:33.559
like to thank you for this, and I also, I know that the slides will be available later,

00:14:33.559 --> 00:14:39.719
so I've also added a couple of resources here to get you started with sass, and

00:14:41.799 --> 00:14:46.840
in case you really want to get into CSS, there's also a couple of bonus slides with

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:55.559
some of the selectors that I think are at least the basic ones that you need to know for CSS.

00:14:56.119 --> 00:15:03.559
So, hopefully this will get you started, and in one year, you'll be thinking, how have I been using

00:15:03.559 --> 00:15:12.200
CSS without sass? Let's talk about speeding up Shiny apps. So, small disclaimer, this is going

00:15:12.200 --> 00:15:19.400
to be just some of the, I think, very important details that you always need to take care of.

00:15:20.119 --> 00:15:27.000
It doesn't mean that you'll be able to speed up everything using just these tips, but hopefully

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:35.000
it will get you started when it comes to at least identify some of the issues that your Shiny app

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.200
might have. So, I'm going to talk about three very important details when it comes to speeding up

00:15:40.200 --> 00:15:45.400
Shiny applications. The first one is update functions. I will also talk a bit about proxy

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:52.280
objects and proxy functions, and then I will finish up by letting you know a bit about custom

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:57.640
messages and browser offloading. I won't get into too much detail, and, of course, every package

00:15:57.640 --> 00:16:03.559
is different and needs different types of optimisations, but hopefully this will help you

00:16:03.559 --> 00:16:11.479
get started. So, update functions. What are update functions? So, update functions are

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:20.840
very simple functions that let you update existing Shiny widgets. So, the important thing here is

00:16:20.840 --> 00:16:29.799
that base Shiny has these, but it's very possible that you're not always using them. So, as an

00:16:29.799 --> 00:16:35.159
example, we have here a very simple Shiny application that has just a checkbox and a

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:42.760
drop-down, and you can see that in our UI, we define a checkbox and we define a UI output,

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:51.159
and then in our server, we simply observe that checkbox and we change our select input label and

00:16:51.159 --> 00:17:01.000
values depending on the state of the checkbox. This feels very standard. This is something that

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:07.560
you probably did quite a lot of times already. However, you can see that we're not really using

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:14.839
any update functions. So, what do I mean by that? What's happening here is that every time we

00:17:14.839 --> 00:17:20.280
trigger a change with the checkbox, we're actually re-rendering the drop-down. So, you can see that,

00:17:21.959 --> 00:17:28.280
because we're using a UI output, and then filling in that UI output with our drop-down,

00:17:29.079 --> 00:17:35.560
what's actually happening behind the scenes is that, whenever this output changes, Shiny is

00:17:35.560 --> 00:17:42.040
removing all the bindings that it created in the background. It creates a new set of bindings for

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:48.920
a new drop-down that just, it does have the same ID, but it's a completely new drop-down,

00:17:49.479 --> 00:17:56.040
and has to rebuild the whole structure. So, this, we can probably do better here,

00:17:56.040 --> 00:18:05.319
and this is where update functions come in. So, if we simply change our codes to, instead of using

00:18:05.319 --> 00:18:13.719
a UI output, to simply render a select input, and then, instead of filling in the UI output,

00:18:13.719 --> 00:18:21.079
we simply use the update select input function, this is completely different. So, in this case,

00:18:21.079 --> 00:18:27.400
what's happening is that there's a call from Shiny being sent to the browser that says, hey,

00:18:28.119 --> 00:18:35.719
update this specific input that already exists in the browser with a new label and some new values.

00:18:36.599 --> 00:18:42.520
So, you can see here that these are very small changes, but it's already

00:18:44.839 --> 00:18:48.280
slightly different approach to how we're actually building the application.

00:18:48.760 --> 00:18:55.800
But does this really matter? And just to give you an example of how, what kind of

00:18:57.079 --> 00:19:01.400
improvements we're talking about, the difference, even for this simple

00:19:03.160 --> 00:19:10.040
drop-down, is actually that for the page to be completely re-rendered and ready for the user to

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:19.079
use, there's a, it goes down from 15 milliseconds to 10 milliseconds. So, just a simple, and we're

00:19:19.079 --> 00:19:24.599
not even talking about the very complex thing that we're doing here, it's just a simple drop-down.

00:19:25.160 --> 00:19:29.880
It's already a massive improvement. So, you can imagine that if we're talking about

00:19:30.520 --> 00:19:36.839
50 drop-downs, 50 elements that we're re-rendering, these really add up very quickly.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:44.599
So, why is this actually better? Like I said, the update function is actually just

00:19:44.599 --> 00:19:50.280
sending a message to the browser and then updating that specific element. So, there's no need to

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:55.719
rebuild anything. It just uses the bindings that Shiny already created for that specific element.

00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:05.719
When it comes to update functions, these are present in most Shiny widgets out of the box.

00:20:05.719 --> 00:20:12.520
So, if you're using even just base Shiny, any kind of input that you create, it probably has a

00:20:12.520 --> 00:20:20.680
corresponding update function. So, action buttons always have an update action button. Select inputs

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:26.439
always have an update select input. And you can see here that there's a bit of a standard where

00:20:26.439 --> 00:20:35.479
the update function is always the name of the UI definition of the widget with a prefix update.

00:20:36.680 --> 00:20:42.439
Of course, always make sure to check the documentation. Usually, these are linked in the

00:20:42.439 --> 00:20:49.079
bottom. After the function definition, you have some information about what kind of

00:20:49.079 --> 00:20:54.040
updates actually exist and what kind of arguments can actually be updated with that function.

00:20:56.119 --> 00:21:03.560
So, these update functions are nice, but what happens when we have slightly more complex

00:21:03.560 --> 00:21:09.479
widgets? And this is the case of when you have, for example, a DT table or an e-charts chart or

00:21:09.479 --> 00:21:15.959
a leaflet map. These usually work slightly different because we're talking about very complex

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:24.359
widgets that a simple update function is probably not enough for everything.

00:21:24.359 --> 00:21:31.400
So, this is where proxies come in. So, proxies are basically a way to reference an existing widget,

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:37.959
an existing complex widget. And then, usually, they have their own set of functions that behave

00:21:37.959 --> 00:21:48.119
similar to update functions, but are applied to that specific instant proxy instance of the

00:21:48.119 --> 00:21:59.319
widget itself. So, a lot of what usually happens is that an example is DT. So, you render, you create

00:21:59.319 --> 00:22:07.640
your data table output, you fill it in with render data table, it creates a table by using...

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:12.760
The way to access the proxy to that element that we just created is actually to use data table

00:22:12.760 --> 00:22:19.640
proxy. So, this is a function that also exists in DT and lets you save a reference to a specific

00:22:19.640 --> 00:22:26.760
table with a specific ID that was defined somewhere else. In this case, it uses the same ID as the data

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:35.400
table output. And you can see that this is basically an example of how you could use proxy.

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:44.119
So, we define our data table output, we fill it in with our render table and some, in this case,

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:52.439
the iris data set. And then, if we save the reference to the proxy of that element using

00:22:52.439 --> 00:22:58.040
data table proxy, we can just manipulate it. So, in this case, we have a small checkbox and every

00:22:58.040 --> 00:23:04.119
time the checkbox changes, we call a specific proxy update function, which in this case is

00:23:04.119 --> 00:23:08.760
select rows, and we just select or don't select the first five rows of the table.

00:23:12.199 --> 00:23:19.880
Exactly. So, one important thing to know here is that different packages also have different

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:26.359
update functions. So, it's important to know to figure out these functions whenever you need to

00:23:26.359 --> 00:23:34.520
use them. Again, documentation is always your friend. So, if you check for this data table

00:23:34.520 --> 00:23:39.640
proxy function, you'll have a lot of information about all the update functions that come with

00:23:39.640 --> 00:23:48.199
that proxy object. And internally, proxy actually works very similar to the update functions that

00:23:48.199 --> 00:23:53.479
I mentioned before. The difference here is that instead of having one update function,

00:23:53.479 --> 00:23:58.199
we actually have a family of update functions and an object to apply it to.

00:24:02.520 --> 00:24:07.719
Again, it's important to check the documentation. You won't always be able to

00:24:08.359 --> 00:24:16.119
update every single thing. So, it's very important to know the family of proxy

00:24:16.119 --> 00:24:22.839
update functions that exist. Hopefully, there will be one that does what you need it to do.

